Project Name: Ethnomusicology Archive: D. K. Wilgus Collection
Name.creator: Wilgus, D. K.|~|Hand, Wayland Debs, 1907-|~|Evans, David, 1944-
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Ethnomusicology Archive
Description.note: With the help of Wayland D. Hand, D. K. Wilgus established Folklore studies at UCLA, and founded the Folklore and Mythology Program in 1965. Wilgus was a folksong and ballad scholar, indefatigable fieldworker, and renowned authority on Anglo-American folksong, "race" records, and "hillbilly" music. He directed five folk music festivals at UCLA. He designed the sound lab and recording studio in the Folklore suite and built the collection of albums and field recordings. For many years Wilgus served as record review editor of the "Journal of American Folklore." As a consequence, he received dozens of albums annually from record companies, and he solicited others gratis. As Chair of the Folklore Program for 17 years he purchased many albums for our archive. Most of the field recordings of American and Irish folk music are his or those of David Evans, one of his students (a noted authority on blues). Not surprisingly then, in the early 1980s the collection of albums and recordings was named the D. K. Wilgus Folksong Archive.|~|Digitization of the field recordings was made possible by a generous grant from the Grammy Foundation.
Title: Wilgus (D.K.) Collection
Description.abstract: The D.K. Wilgus Folksong Collection consists of approximately 8,000 commercially recorded albums of traditional music, song, and narrative as well as 1,000 field-recorded tapes.

Description.note: Performers: Mrs. Tillie Pursell; Mr. Herschel Slavin.|~|All titles are merely for general content.  They are not the titles that are associated with the songs because the singer could not recall them.|~|Recorded by: Esther Pursell|~|Mrs. Tillie Pursell:The Rabbie Does Wonders - Jewish;Don't Worry My Dear - Russian (tongue in cheeck song) (melody like Norweigian "The Younger Generation";Play, Play, Be Gay - Jewish (Resembles "Hullabaloo Belay").Mr. Herschel Slavin:Forgive My Sins - Hebrew;Hebrew Chant - Hebrew;Hebrew Chant - Hebrew (The singer paces as he sings and at one point walked out of the range of the microphone.).Mrs. Tillie Pursell:Listen My Pupils - Jewish;The Jew is Crying - Jewish (singer could not remember third stanza);The Czar's Manifesto - Russian (words listed under Underground Activities in collector's notes);Teaching the Children Their A B Cs - Jewish;I Left My Home for Israel - Yiddish and Hebrew (singer had difficulty in remembering the words);Dark Eyes Have Fire - Jewish;Two White Doves are on My Window -  Jewish (love song);Lullaby - Russian (Traditional);I Only Have One Dime and That Dime's Not Mine - Hebrew;The Bird's Message - Jewish;Bim Bam Bom - Jewish (Passing of the Sabbath);The Scholar's Dream - Jewish (singer's comment - It's rather Faust like);Where Were You When Life was Sweet? - Jewish;Where the Girls Go, I Go - Russian (soldier's song) (singer could not remember the chorus);Oh Rabbi Tell Me - Russian-Jewish (written by Frugg);The Preacher's Dog - Russian (nonsense);The Harvest - Russian-Jewish (written by Frugg).|~|Title from tape: Pursell * Russian & Jewish Songs
Title: Russian and Jewish Folksongs Part 1
Format.medium: sound tape reels : 7 1/2 ips, two track, mono.
Relation.isPartOf: Archive of California and Western Folklore

Side II Strike Music of American Labor: Hallelujah I'm a Bum (Greenway?); Pie in the Sky; Solidarity Forever; Union Maid - (a dub of the Almanac Singers record); Talking Union - (a dub of the Almanac Singers record); Sister Jenny's Turn to Throw the Ball; Ludlow Massacre - Woody Guthrie; Which Side - Almanacs; Join the NMU; Harry Sims; Fight for Union Recognition (tune: I've been workig on the railroad); The Boatmakers' Union is a No Good Union. Description.note: The Legend of the Mark of the Palm on the Parapet of the Bridge in Limrick, Ireland Province of Munster;The Appearance of the Soul;SPIRITS:a. The Old Lady With the Red Shawl;b. Iran); 45 rpm recordings Leyla Jan (Sistan, S. E. Iran); Sardar Amad Be Sistan (Sistan, S. E. Iran); Kharom Sharsharia; Garan Chapi Sorna - Dohol; Bivasa Donya
Title: Iranian & Serbian Recordings
Relation.isPartOf: Archive of California and Western Folklore

Description.note: Recorded by: Marina Bokelman|~|Title from tape: M.* Lady Lore|~|WISHING ON A STAR - wishbone; candles on a birthday cake; LAST PIECE OF CAKE MEANS YOU'LL BE A WIDOW; WEDDINGS - throwing the boquet [sic]; rice, what to take on a honeymoon; IT'S BAD LUCK TO WEAR SOMETHING NEW TO A FUNERAL; TABOOS CONCERNING A WEDDING; SUPERSTITIONS ABOUT CLOTHING; IT'S BAD LUCK TO - break a mirror, sweep someone's foot, step over things, bring an old broom (or mop) into a new house, sweep after dark; SPECIAL MEALS ON NEW YEAR'S DAY; SUPERSTITIONS ABOUT CHRISTMAS TREES; WHAT YOU TKE INTO A NEW HOUSE; BACK OUT THE BACK DOOR; IF YOU GO THROUGH A DOOR WITH NO HINGES SAY "GOOD LUCK FOLLOW ME"; WHAT WILL HAPPEN IF YOUR PALM (EYE) ITCHES; EAR BURNS; QUIETING OR DISTURBING THE DEAD; COVERING MIRRORS AFTER A FUNERAL; HOW TO DISPOSE OF A PERSON'S POSSESSIONS AFTER HIS DEATH; THE DEAD INFLUENCE BABIES; AN ELDERLY PERSON IS NEVER SUPPOSED TO SLEEP WITH A BABY; IF YOU START SEWING SOMETHING ON YOUR PERIOD YOU SHOULD FINISH IT BEFORE THE PERIOD IS OVER; DON'T UNDERTAKE ANY NEW FINANCIAL PROBLEMS ON FRIDAY THE THIRTEENTH; 13 IS UNLUCKY BECAUSE IT DENOTES THE LAST SUPPER; A BLACK CAT ACROSS YOUR PATH IS UNLUCKY; IF YOU PUT YOUR CLOTHES ON INSIDE OUT IT IS BAD LUCK TO CHANGE THEM; IF DOGS BARK AT MIDNIGHT THERE WILL BE A STORM; DOGS BARK WHEN THEIR MASTER DIES; YOU ARE CLOSE TO DEATH WHEN YOU SNEEZE; MOTHER'S ACTIVITIES DURING PREGNANCY INFLUENCE CHILD'S TENDENCIES AFTER BIRTH; YOU CAN INFLUENCE CHILDREN BY TALKING TO THEM WHILE THEY SLEEP; STAINS COME OUT WITH VINEGAR AND SALT; SPILL SALT ON A WINE STAIN; KEEP ANIMALS AWAY FROM CHILDREN; IF YOU BREAK ANYTHING, THROW ALL THE PIECES AWAY TOGETHER IN A BAG; PIERCING EARS HELPS HEARING

Description.note: Recorded by: Marina Bokelman|~|SUPERSTITIONS:To meet a priest is bad luck; one turns a button to neutralize the effects; New York superstitions; Knives and pins; If you put your slip on inside-out it will be bad luck.INDIVIDUAL BELIEF: If someone cleans house after you leave, it is an insult.DEATH CUSTOMS:Washing hands before entering house of the deceased after the funeral; Covering mirrors; Comfort; Shiva; Giving away of deceased's belongings - wait 8 days; Slashing of suit lapel - the suit lapel of the near male relative's is slashed.TALK ABOUT UNEXPECTED GRANDMOTHER;TALK ABOUT MIXED MARRIAGE;BELIEFS:Departure; Travel; Menstruation.REMEDY FOR RUDDY HANDS;OMENS:New arrivals; Weather indicators; Money; Shiverieing [sic].ANECDOTE ABOUT RUSSIAN PEASANT;ANECDOTE ABOUT UKRANIAN LAZINESS;ANECDOTE ABOUT URINATION;ANECDOTE ABOUT BAR MITZVAH;ANECDOTE ABOUT YIDDISH GRANDMOTHER;STORY ABOUT MARRIAGE BROKER;TEXT OF SONG BY CESAR CUI - MATCHMAKERS;TALK ABOUT QUALITIES OF GERMAN DIALECTS;TALK ABOUT SIMILARITIES BETWEEN LANGUAGES;STORY ABOUT A DUTCHMAN IN THE HOSPITAL;STORY ABOUT A YIDDISH SUBWAY RIDER;ANOTHER STORY ABOUT A YIDDISH SUBWAY RIDER.|~|Performer: Sema Lighter|~|Location: Venice, CA.|~|Title from tape: Lighter * Bokelman
Title: Beliefs
Format.medium: sound tape reels : 3 3/4 ips, two track, mono.
Relation.isPartOf: Archive of California and Western Folklore

Project Name: Ethnomusicology Archive: D. K. Wilgus Collection

Description.note: Recorded by: Marina Bokelman|~|TALK ABOUT GYPSIES;STORIES OF RELIEF WORK:Story about Gypsies; Story about Palestinians.ANECDOTE ABOUT BIRTH CONTROL;Story of Relief work - Scotch Woman.CUSTOM OF SAYING ONLY GOOD THINGS ABOUT THE DECEASED;TALK ABOUT ELEPHANT JOKES;GRAPE ANECDOTE;SONG - "Thanking the heart; it's so wonderful, receptive and knows how to love.";THE FLEA;THE ORGAN-GRINDER by Schubert;THE COUSIN;"Drinking whisky, drinking wine...";"Should I be a rabbi...";STORY ABOUT HOW THE GRANDCHILDREN LOVED THEIR JEWISH GRANDMOTHER;GERMAN STORY ABOUT MOTHER'S LOVER FOR HER SON [sic];STORIES AND TALK ABOUT MRS. MENENDEZ (FAMILY ACQUAINTANCE);TALK ABOUT LUCIFER MENENDEZ;TALK ABOUT JOSE MENENDEZ.|~|Performer: Sema Lighter|~|Location: Venice, CA.
Title: Lighter * Bokelman

Description.note: Collected by: Irving and Reba Bass|~|Content: Various subjects. Locations: North Hollywood, California; Los Angeles, California; Ohai California; Canoga Park, California. Side 1A: Curse: I hope you go to your levia tomorrow; Curse (Yiddish): Afta Gonnuf Bren Ta Hittel; Expression (Yiddish): Reply to what's new: On the Roof...; General discussion; Jokes: Jew and Irishman in hospital; Jewish couple in court to obtain divorce; Variant of above; Jewish man writes to wife in old country and snds her things; Bald man meets man with hair; Couples spending their 25th wedding anniversary; A couple's experience with a Paris artist; Englishman marries; General discussion; Joke: Rabbi and Rabbitzen at the Mikveh. Side 1B: Bonybean History; Norht African Hunters and Fisherman; Meanterthal (The Tall Meander); Cro-Magnon (Grandpa-Cro); How the informant got the name "Burr"; How his family got to Central America (The Bonybean Tribe); Uncle Contiki; Origin of the saying "He's gone south"; Piedra Blanca; The invention of the bow; Discovering the ships of the sea; How lion canyon got its name; Little Shehan and Grandma Skinnyfingers; Grandma Skinnifingers' club; How the informant got the name "Wallace"; THe last of the Bonybean Tribe; How Wallace got a wife. Side 2A: Lil (poem); Here's to Mag (poem); Frigging in the rigging (good ship venus) (song); One-Eyed Reilly (song); Pilot Told Me Before He Died (song); Way Down by the River Perdec (song); Queen of all the Acrobats (song); Last Saturday Night (song); Good Old Mountain Dew (song); Meet Me by the Slop Shute (song); Story of a Cat - Sam the Fraternity Man (song); Gay Cavallero (song). Side 2B: West Point march; Presentation Day; The Fouth Class System; "Kissing Rock" on "Flirtation Walk"; The Stone Eagle on the doorway of Washington Hall; The Statue of General Sedgewick; The cadet of France statue from Le Col Polytechnique; West Point Alma Matre (origin and text of the song); The Core (origin and text of the song); Benny Haven's Oh (origin and text of the song); Army Blue (origin and text of the song); On Brave Old Army Team (song). Side 2C: The rock jumped when the rooster crowed (riddle); Trying to get bread, jam, and butter, to comeout even (riddle); The cows' legs matched the mountain (riddle); Come O Cao (tongue twister); Had an Old Mule (poem); Eeny-Meeny-Miney-Mo (counting out rhyme); Oh! The Buzzards, They Fly High (song). Tape #4, continued from tape 65/26. Note: Performers: Jeanette Machat; Louis Machat; Mike Hendin; Wallace Burr; Delta Songs; Christopher Lambides; Kathy Morgan|~|Title from tape: Yiddish Folk Speech #4 - Bass * Bonyben|~|Locations: North Hollywood, California; Los Angeles, California.

Description.note: Performer: Ollie Gilbert|~|Rose of White;Green Corn - banjo solo (first time she played the gourd banjo);Green Corn - Uncle Dave Macon Style - banjo solo;Little Brown Jog - banjo solo;Old Fashioned Sugar Hill - banjo solo;Soldier's Joy (she had sung bawdy verses previously for Ebby Wilgus, but would not record them.) - banjo solo;Black-eyed Susie - banjo solo;Waltz - title unknown - banjo solo;Waltz - title unknown - banjo solo;Fox Chase - banjo solo;Untitled banjo solo - (Goin' Downtown?);Lord Bateman (fragment);Come all you Brisk Young Cowboys;Song Composed by Joseph Loveny (?) on this death bed;(a discussion of songs she knows - with fragments - not listed on sheets);The Tom Cat Song (learned from her husband);Rattlesnakin' Daddy;(many fragments occur here);"On a dark stormy night the angels called mother" - (fragment) words Ollie read "somewhere" which she set to tune of "Precious Jewel";Haunted House;The Rich Lady (The Brown Girl);Old Joe Clark - (Fragment) - plus fragments "The Warship had landed" Nightingale etc.|~|Title from tape: Ollie Gilbert * Wilgus|~|Recorded by: Ebby and D.K. Wilgus

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Ethnomusicology Archive
Description.note: Title from tape: Ollie Gilbert * Wilgus|~|Pretty Polly (Polly Oliver);Lightning Express - fragment;True and Trembling Brakeman - fragment;Lord Bateman - fragment and prose summary;Two Brothers - fragment;Lone Pilgrim;Rank Stranger;Cole Younger;Brother Green ("That's old Civil War and my mother said/that/indicates her mother was 5 or 7 when war broke out -- but was born in 1868/ she remembers -- she was standing at a little cleft tree," "soldiers passed by her beating a drum -- and she heard someone singing the song.  This passage is not clear.  - Apparently her mother (who may have been born in 1858) was standing by a cleft tree or bush when someone came by playing fifes and drums.  The patted her on the head.  Then she moved somewhere else and heard the song, and the people who sang the song were somehow related to the brother in the song.;Rough and Rowdy Boys;Utah Carl - Learned from her brother in Little Rock about 40 years ago.;Tramp in the Rain/Can I Sleep in your Barn Tonight, Mister?;Lilla Lee - learned from mother;Charming Beauty Bright - learned from mother;"At the foot of yonders mountain where there runs a clear stream" - from mother;Cottage on a Hillside - read text in a book about 1919 - set it to a tune herself.;Three Little Babes (Wife of Usher's Well);The Little Family (incomplete?)|~|Recorded by: Ebby and D.K. Wilgus|~|Performer: Ollie Gilbert
Title: clym200203acwf031-65_side2-01
Relation.isPartOf: Archive of California and Western Folklore

Description.note: Collected by: Mrs. Anne M. Evans|~|Performer: Mrs. Eliza Carey|~|1. Clover blossoms used to cure skin diseases;2. Mutton tallow used to cure sore hands;3. Beef's gall and alcohol used to cure cuts, infections;4. Turpentine on sugar used to cure colic. (appendicitis);5. Snake's head plant used to cure worms. (tapeworms);6. Motherwort plant used for females ailments;7. White and red clover used to cure pimples;8. Cure for worms contributed Mrs. Evans;9. Pennyroyal and peppermint plant used to cure fevers;10. Wild cherry tonic;11. Leeches;12. Ground hemlock used to restore hair;13. Hot poultices used for toothaches;14. Hops grown around privies;15. Ringworms cured by sulphur put on cold steel;16. Mud used to cure beestings;17. Long life in her family. lack of sanitation;18. Talk about her relatives in Nova Scotia;19. Salt herring filets bound on feet to cure colds;20. Tea leaves used to cure styes;21. Bread poultices used to cure boils on fingers;22. Skin from eggshell used to draw boils;23. Pneumonia cured by cornmeal and onion poultices;24. Black flies (Spanish) bound over heart to cure Mrs. Carey's heart ailment (used by a doctor!).|~|Title from tape: Carey * Evans|~|Location: Georgetown, MA.

Red sumac syrup used to cure coughs;7. Warts given by toads, frogs, beavers;8. Warts cured by raw chicken put in crotch of tree in dark of moon. When it went away, the warts went away;9. Saliva used to cure warts;10. Old shoe or mocassin chewed for stomach ailments;11. Croup cured by drinking mother's hot urine. (She read article about this cure later);12. Cow manure poultices of pigeon dung used for cures;13. Tobacco poultices used for many things;14. "Commercial travellers" who sold medicines. Carter's Little Liver Pills;15. Description.note: Recorded by Colin D. Edwards at UCLA for CBC Studios in Toronto|~|"Witchcraft" - a sound encyclopedia composed of a conversation with Dr. Wayland d. Hand, Professor  of German and Folklore, University of California, Los Angeles, conducted by Colin D. Edwardsfirst section (29 min.30sec)|~|Side II Religious objects used to combat witches Churches' attitude toward witchcraft Court of law and witchcraft cases Geographical aspects of witchcraft beliefs Persecution of witches - down to today Stake-through-the-heart method of killing - in Northern Europe and America Discussion of Dr. Hand's Book Current sources of information on witchcraft *current beliefs Geometric designs to keep off witches Birds associated with witches Witchcraft due to need for scapegoat, sadism, mass hysteria Need for the Supernatural and fantastic, cultism Lack of witch-organization; witches' sabbath Flying Weather for witches Esoteric nature of witch-society. Lack of hangers-on in the normal world Scapegoat aspect: witch is the result of need for a scapegoat, people with idiosyncracies were singled out as a witch, witch beliefs always result from some real or fancied wrong
Title: "Witchcraft" (interview/conversation) part 2
Format.medium: open reel tape
Relation.isPartOf: Archive of California and Western Folklore

Name.creator: Hand, Wayland D.
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Ethnomusicology Archive
Description.note: Recorded by Colin D. Edwards at UCLA for CBC Studios in Toronto|~|Side I Origin and antiquity of Witchcraft Similarities and differences: witch, witch doctor, medicine man Self-consciousness of witches - people in the community decide who is a witch Role in community - isolation and difference Witches' powers Image of witch - Germanic Europe in particular - physically Witches stake becomes broomstick Burning at the stake: ability to change physical form (usually into animal form), witches' familiar Witch-riding - witch rides human beings during the night, 1890 actual case involving witch-riding, this can also happen to animals Ruination of fields Witch/Wizard distinction - why no male witches Becoming a witch: acts of sacriligious nature, pact with the devil; physical and spiritual, witches' sabbaths and initiation rites Institutionalized witchcraft - 1489 start Encyclopedia of Witchcraft - published by 2 theologians Married and unmarried women as witches Methods of counteracting witches Methods of counteracting witches: the use of iron and steel fastened about entrances to the premises such as a horseshoe over the door, a sieve or flour sifter near keyhole, chimney, window, scissors - particularly open in the form of a Christian cross, plants; all hardwood protects against witches, oak, ash, beech, birch, maple, hickory, which hazel, mustard seed in Latin America because she has to count the seeds and witches are bad counters, when witches work at night steal their skin and salt it with red pepper. When they put their skin back on they will burn to death, shoot witch in effigy with a silver bullet to kill Werewolf/witch similarities: change or turn skin - creatures who can get out of their skin Sacred objects (esp. Bible) used to combat witches Household objects used to combat witches|~|"Witchcraft" - a sound encyclopedia composed of a conversation with Dr. Wayland d. Hand, Professor  of German and Folklore, University of California, Los Angeles, conducted by Colin D. Edwardsfirst section (29 min.30sec)
Title: "Witchcraft" (interview/conversation) part 1
Format.medium: open reel tape
Relation.isPartOf: Archive of California and Western Folklore
